&start=21&stop=40>2</a><a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm25.showMessageRange?topicID=8.topic&start=41&stop=60>3</a><a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm25.showMessageRange?topicID=8.topic&start=61&stop=65>4</a> </td><td align=right> <br> <a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm25.showMessage?topicID=11.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm25.showMessage?topicID=10.topic"> Next Topic >> </a> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95% cellpadding=5 cellspacing=1><tr><td valign=top  class=headings><font color=#333399>Author</font></td><td valign=top  class=headings><font color=#333399>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 10:46:02 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> Here's a basic truth: EVERY PEN &amp; PAPER RPG IS BASED ON PvP.  And by PvP, I mean human conflict...conflict between human-controlled characters.<br>
<br>
When you attack an NPC of any sort, you really are attacking characters controlled by the person sitting across the table...the GM.  In every game I've played, the GMs have all been human (although it might be questionable in some cases).<br>
<br>
You can also attack PCs...characters controlled by the person sitting next to you.  This rarely happens, and with good reason.  But the potential for it is still there.  And if roleplayed well and in context, it can lead to some of the more memorable gaming sessions you will ever have.<br>
<br>
In either case you expect to be held accountable for your actions.  And that is probably the key distinction between P&amp;P RPGs and MMORPGs.  In MMORPGs, players feel that they can escape accountability for their actions.  And by and large, they can.  The problem is how to incorporate the potential of human conflict in an MMORPG without it overrunning and ruining the game.<br>
<br>
The problem might be summed up as follows: A little spice enhances the broth; too much spoils the soup.<br>
<br>
There are a number of MMORPGs coming out in the next year or two that seek to solve this problem.  EQ tried to do this by incorporating a PvP switch, but getting rid of the potential of human conflict isn't a real &quot;solution.&quot;<br>
<br>
A PvP switch in an RPG is the equivalent of a lobotomy.  The more ways you limit player choice in a RPG, the less of a roleplaying game it is.  The point of a RPG is for you to put yourself into the shoes of your character, and act and react as if you were that character.   <br>
<br>
One &quot;ideal&quot; of a good RPG is to have no effective difference between PCs and NPCs in the game.  After all, to your character, the terms PC and NPC are meaningless: they are people, animals, monsters, etc.  Being able to attack NPCs but not PCs abrogates that ideal.  (Of course, EQ abrogates it in other ways, as well.  But EQ is not really a fully-fledged RPG in a lot of ways.)<br>
<br>
The fact that there is a large population of griefers out there ready to romp in any MMORPG they can doesn't change the above analysis.  It just means that to have a true RPG online, you have to take the griefers into account.  <br>
<br>
UO struggled with this, and by and large failed.  DAC and AO have presented different takes on ways to include some of the &quot;spice&quot;  of human conflict without &quot;spoiling the soup.&quot; Star Wars Galaxies also has a fresh take (Raph says he has learned from the attempts to control PvP in UO).<br>
<br>
How much &quot;spice&quot; depends on the game.  Some games, in fact, like Shadowbane, make the PvP element the primary focus of the game.  Whether this appeals to you is a matter of personal taste.  I personally like the way DAC is going: you don't have to engage in PvP, but there is a focused, directed PvP element in the end game.  <br>
<br>
Whether they will succeed or not remains to be seen.  But I applaud any attempt to include the possibility of PC conflict in an MMORPG.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A> at: 7/6/01 12:24:35 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usorrun.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sorrun</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 12:07:30 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> This is what happens when we let Scirocco moderate a section.. he gets into "thinker" mode and next thing we know the Illiad spits out.<br>
