<br>
A GM can make sure that the Red Dragon that the PCs just wandered upon is "lost in thought..." or otherwise not hungry, so that the entire party that took 3 REAL hours to get to where it was going is not eaten in a single round of combat.<br>
<br>
Try wandering up to Nagafen and see how much pitty you get walking into his lair...<br>
<br>
Basically, it is "Rules-Bending" that makes PvP acceptable and fun.  This is impossible to do without interaction between GM and Player durring 100% of the session.<br>
<br>
Server Games will always fail at PvP (IMHO) due to the fact that "Server AI" instead of a thoughtful-GM will be making the majority of player-affecting decisions.<br>
<br>
Now... take a game like NeverWinter Nights where a player is acting as GM, and you have my interest. <p><table width="600" border="0" height="138">
