<br>
Just because there is a person controlling (somewhat) the actions of the NPC doesn't make it PvP.  The GM has certain rough rules of behavior to follow with each NPC.<br>
<br>
Take GM events for instance, they are *not* pvp even though both sides of the conflict are controlled by humans.  The NPCs in GM events are following a set script with a small amount of variation.<br>
<br>
PvP is about killing other players that have about the same options you do.  NPCs are not groomed and lvl'd and equipped, they are simply spawned (created).  <br>
<br>
PvP brings out the worst in people, period.  Anytime you have a situation where you give grief players the tools they need to screw over other people, you're going to have serious problems.<br>
<br>
I don't think you can argue that P&amp;P games turned people into exploiting ego-maniacs.  The fact that the EQ pvp servers have an almost unlimited stream of CS problems kinda speaks for itself. <p><IMG SRC="http://lordfate.homestead.com/files/misc/sig.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ueqaquinas.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EQAquinas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 1:52:09 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> <i>And that is probably the key distinction between P&P RPGs and MMORPGs. In MMORPGs, players feel that they can escape accountability for their actions. </i><br>
<br>
I’m not sure I see PvP combat as the reason for this difference.  I can see at least two other factors (in addition to the human factor mentioned by Paldor) that, in my view, are more important.  First is the size of the community.  A P&P game is typically played amongst a handful of people who know each other in real life.  If you act like a jerk, you’re going to feel the consequences pretty quickly.  A MMORPG is played among thousands of people who have no connection outside the game, and don’t even know each others’ real names.  Think of the difference between being rude at the office where you work, and being rude to random people on the streets of a big city; the former is much more likely to get you in trouble.<br>
<br>
Second, people in a P&P game can control who inhabits their world.  If someone acts like a jerk to people in a P&P game, pretty soon he won’t be invited back.  As a result, a regular P&P group is likely to consist of people who not only know each other, but who tend to have similar ideas about what is and is not fun roleplaying.  In a MMORPG, you have no control over who else logs on.  Sure, theoretically you could get someone banned, but that’s much harder to do than just agreeing that Bob is a jerk and not inviting him over the next time you play D&D.<br>
<br>
Actually, I wonder if you don’t have the causal relationship backwards.  Instead of the absence of PvP leading to a lack of accountability, I think it’s the lack of accountability that’s lead to the absence of PvP.  Game designers have come to realize that if you set people loose in a virtual world with the ability to kill each other, and without some mechanism to create consequences for killing people, the results aren’t pretty.  Consider the history of the industry since UO’s release and the resulting gankfest (from what I’ve read, I didn’t play): the introduction of penalties for PK’ing and then a new UO world without PvP; the release of AC and EQ largely without PvP; and a great deal of effort given to assuring people that future PvP systems will be different because there will be consequences for wanton PK’ing.  Designers seem to view accountability is a prerequisite for robust PvP, not the other way around.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 4:26:57 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;&quot;Server Games will always fail at PvP (IMHO) due to the fact that &quot;Server AI&quot; instead of a thoughtful-GM will be making the majority of player-affecting decisions.&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually, if the Server AI is making the decisions (e.g., controlling the dragon), then what you really have is a failure of PvE, not PvP, correct?  After all, you've replaced the human controlling the dragon (or the bandits, or whatever) with AI.  <br>
<br>
If it is true that Server AI cannot replace the human intelligence, then doesn't this make allowing the potential conflict between player-controlled characters even more important, to supply that human element that is missing?   <br>
<br>
As I stated above, PvP in pen and paper RPGs is NOT limited to players vs. GM...it also includes players vs. player.  Remember, by PvP, I mean conflict between human-controlled characters.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;Just because there is a person controlling (somewhat) the actions of the NPC doesn't make it PvP.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, it does. It's conflict between human controlled characters (which I am careful to state in my lead paragraph).   And there's no &quot;somewhat&quot; about the GM-controlled characters.  <br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;The GM has certain rough rules of behavior to follow with each NPC.&quot;<br>
<br>
As do the players, if they are role playing.  If they're not role playing, it's not an RPG, is it?  And I am limiting my discussion to RPGs.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;Take GM events for instance, they are *not* pvp even though both sides of the conflict are controlled by humans. The NPCs in GM events are following a set script with a small amount of variation.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, it's PvP. See my definition of PvP above.  I don't want to get tied up in nomenclature...it's conflict between human-controlled characters that forms the core of pen and paper RPGs.<br>
<br>
GMs are not bound by &quot;set scripts&quot; any more than players.  The GM is supposed to be playing those characters according to their roles, reacting to what the players do or say as if the GM were those characters.  And THAT is exactly what the players are doing with their characters...acting in role.  <br>
<br>
Of course, if your GMs have never acted like this, have never given life to your encounters in the game, then you have my sympathies.  Your pen and paper RPG experience has been sub-par, IMO.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;PvP is about killing other players that have about the same options you do. NPCs are not groomed and lvl'd and equipped, they are simply spawned (created).&quot;<br>
<br>
PvP is about conflict between human controlled characters.  Human conflict is at the core of nearly all of the best stories out there, whether in novel, movie, or some other form.  There are some exceptions, but rare.<br>
<br>
With your reference to spawning of NPCs, I think you've jumped back to MMORPGs, correct?  If so, you are making my point for me.  The NPCs in a pen and paper game are created by the GM to add life to the adventure (if you had a GM that did nothing more than roll dice to create something to kill with no interaction with you, then you have my pity, as I said above).  Even more important than the way they are created, is the way they are CONTROLLED.  A good GM will add that element to an encounter even with 1d12 randomly rolled kobolds.  <br>
<br>
And yes, you are right that that is what is missing in the PvE element of MMORPGs.  All the more reason not to eliminate the PvP element.<br>
 <br>
<br>
