</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 5:02:07 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/rtfm.gif width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> Of course Scirocco is correct here, I agree 100%.  :)<br>
<br>
I would go even further though -- I think you CANNOT have an effective MMRPG without a <b>meaningful</b> PvP option (meaningful = well thought out, balanced, and effective, i.e. not EQ).  Without meaningful PvP, you dig yourself into a corner and it gets harder and harder to maintain player interest.  Meaningful PvP helps the players govern themselves, form communities, and test their abilities not against some dumb AI which can be defeated using a standard cookie-cutter method, but against a live human being who doesn't need a server patch to change his reaction.<br>
<br>
As Scirocco pointed out, in the pen & paper games the DM controls the actions of each of the non-player characters, which gives the game the same sort of excitement as a PvP game.  Since this is typically impossible in a MMRPG, PvP is the answer.<br>
<br>
I know that after EQ, I will never again experiment with a MMRPG that doesn't offer a meaningful PvP option -- and I doubt any software developers will write one. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0> at: 7/6/01 5:02:33 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uleana2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Leana 2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 5:28:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> Without getting into a serious discussion there’s a simplified way to look at this.<br>
<br>
What do you like?  Do you like to test your skills against other players in a head-to-head fashion? <br>
<br>
I think that most players like to test themselves against other RL players.  In EQ you test yourself against other players all the time.  You just test yourself by judging your accomplishments against theirs.  How fast did you get to 50?  What gear are you wearing?  Have you ever soloed the Dino in OOT?  The only thing missing is the head-to-head fight that only leaves one person breathing at the end.<br>
<br>
UO left a nasty taste in the mouths of the MMORPG player base pertaining to PvP.   I come from an Meridian 59 background, and I can tell you for certain... Good PvP adds a great deal of dimension to an online RPG.  With good PvP there are times when your pulse will pound, your fingers will shake on the keyboard, and you will die a little when your character is slain by that cheese eating bastard that snuck in behind you.<br>
<br>
I miss PvP, and I agree with the &quot;S&quot; man, a little spice adds a lot, and too much ruins the whole dish.<br>
<br>
I also like the looks of DAoC.  Limited PvP, and the topper for me is the fact that the PvP has a purpose.  You don’t kill just cause you’re more leet than the other character your killing.  You kill for realm points and relics to help your realm.<br>
<br>
In closing let me say this.  EQ is a GREAT game.  It broke ground in many ways, and made many of the games getting ready to come out possible by showing that a MMORPG could be a huge success.  The only two things that could have made EQ better would be these:<br>
<br>
1:  A more balanced PvP system.  By this I mean better geography to promote PvP while not letting it run amok.  More equanimity between classes and their ability to kill.  More equanimity between groups of lower players Vs. a higher level character.<br>
<br>
2:  Better customer relations.  More CS reps, a more defined set of rules, just better relations across the board.<br>
