<br>
I don't disagree.  This is what I was getting with my reference to RPG with a lobotomy...:) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthedruidsgrove.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=brillig>Brillig</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/6/01 6:41:59 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hmm</span><hr size=1> Heya:<br>
<br>
 &quot;And by PvP, I mean human conflict...conflict between human-controlled characters.&quot;<br>
<br>
 I understand that this is what _you_ mean when you say 'PvP', but I wonder how many folks accept this definition.  I certainly don't.  To me, 'PvP' means &quot;player versus player conflict&quot;.  I don't consider GMs as players.  I agree that PnP RPGs often have interparty conflict, but I think only in an extreme minority would one be able to say such a game is &quot;based on&quot; this sort of interaction.  It seems to me that most PnP games are mostly PvE.<br>
<br>
 Aside: Rules Lawyers are PvV, substitute V with GM, the game's name, etc. ;)<br>
<br>
 On the other hand, I'll likely play DAoC and participate in the PvP there (after level 30, right?).  I _like_ cooperative games, lots.  And there are _tons_ of competitive games out there already.  It sometimes annoys me how the fricking realtime crowd insists that _all_ games be realtime.  Well, I want some turnbased games, darnit.  It sometimes annoys me how the fricking multiplayer crowd insists that _all_ games have multiplayers.  Well, I like single player-focused games, sometimes.  Etc. with PvP vs PvE. ;)<br>
<br>
Take care,<br>
Brillik <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/7/01 7:08:37 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmm</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;I don't consider GMs as players<br>
<br>
GMs are as much participants of the game as the people you refer to as &quot;players.&quot;  And since participants of games are players of the game, by definition, GMs ARE players.  <br>
<br>
Don't get caught up in the nomenclature.  In the online world, people distinguish between PvP and PvE.  What is the REAL difference between the two?  One is HI controlled, one is AI controlled.  That's all.<br>
<br>
Would it make you feel better to use the term HCCvHCC (human controlled character)?<br>
<br>
BTW, PvV is a form of indirect PvP.  Verant is responding to what players do by making changes in the game design, including the actions of the AI.  <br>
<br>
My point in bringing this up is to respond to the knee-jerk reaction many people have to the presence of HCCvHCC in MMORPGs (most people do call it PvP).  What they don't realize is that HCCvHCC is THE basis of a P&amp;P RPG.  Most people don't have a problem with it in the latter, and in fact, without the HCCvHCC (or PvP), most people wouldn't play them.   How many successful P&amp;P one-person RPGs do you know of?<br>
<br>
Here's what RPGs are missing: immediacy and accountability.  Many people playing these games still, at some level, don't really think of the fact that there is a real human being behind that other character.  The other person isn't sitting across the table.  And there are many who take the advantage of causing grief to another human being for the pleasure of it, and do so because they feel they cannot be held accountable for it.  Or they feel that whatever accounting will be made will be relatively insignificant.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utsukune.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tsukune</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/7/01 7:39:41 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://home.nycap.rr.com/tsukune/wicket.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> PvP is player vs player conflict.  Players are not GMs.  GMs have the power to change the world in a sentance.  Players don't.<br>
<br>
A GM is not the players enemy.  The GM is there to create encounters and to enforce the rules.  To this end, the GM will control NPCs to oppsose the players.  Many of the NPCs are created for the sole purpose of dieing to the PCs.  The GM spawns these NPCs as needed.<br>
<br>
Most PnP games do not have much, or encourage any PvP.  Player conflict tends to be the death of a PnP game, since the GM cannot divide his time between two teams operating seperately, and without controlling one side of the conflict, cannot guide the story along.<br>
<br>
When Players decide the game is not PvE, but rather PvGM, the only action players can take is to quit.<br>
<br>
Verant is a GM, not a player.  They have to divide their attention between thousands of players over hundreds of simultaneous encounters.  Since this would be an impossible task to accomplish manually, they have automated the process.  They set the rules in stone (as opposed to most GMs who bend or break rules in the interest of the story).  And with a divided player base, PvP is a possibility between players.<br>
<br>
When Players decide the game is not PvE (or PvP), but rather PvV, the only action players can take is to quit. <p><A HREF="http://www.serenity-within.com"><img src ="http://home.nycap.rr.com/tsukune/sig1.gif" alt="Tsukune - Serenity Within" ></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/7/01 8:53:33 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;&quot;Players are not GMs. GMs have the power to change the world in a sentance. Players don't.&quot;<br>
<br>
Doesn't matter.  They're both actively participating in the game, controlling characters in the game, and hopefully playing those characters according to their respective roles.<br>
<br>
All you are pointing out is a difference in the power of the participants.  Why is that relevant?  Moreover, you overlook the fact that there can be a similar difference in the power of the &quot;players&quot; (the non-GMs).  Not to mention the fact that a player in a P&amp;P RPG DOES have the power to change the world in a sentence just as much as a GM.  <br>
<br>
A GM and a player are not that different, since the interactive storytelling that is a RPG requires the mutual consent and cooperation of everyone involved.  <br>
<br>
A GM says, &quot;Lightning comes out of the sky and kills all your characters.&quot;  The players are free to say, &quot;No it doesn't, we continue to ride along.&quot;  Why?  Because it's all in their imaginations.   Without the mutual consent of the &quot;players,&quot; it doesn't matter what the GM says.  <br>
<br>
It works the other way, too, of course.   The players say, &quot;We swing our swords and kill all 100 orcs at once.&quot;  The GM says, &quot;Sorry, 99 of them are still alive.&quot;  Once again, mutual consent is needed.<br>
<br>
A GM can only change the world with a sentence if all the other participants in the RPG consent to it.  A &quot;player&quot; can do the same thing as well, if all the other participants consent.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;A GM is not the players enemy.&quot;<br>
<br>
I never used the word &quot;enemy.&quot;  Why do you?  Just because some other human is controlling a character that your conflict is in conflict with doesn't make them your enemy.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;The GM is there to create encounters and to enforce the rules. To this end, the GM will control NPCs to oppose the players.&quot;<br>
<br>
Too restrictive, and you're wrong.  A GM controls characters called &quot;NPCs&quot; to INTERACT with the CHARACTERS controlled the non-GM humans playing the game (&quot;players&quot;).  The fact that you use the word &quot;oppose&quot; indicates to me that your RPGing experience must be somewhat limited.  The fact that you refer to the NPCs opposing the PLAYERS (and not characters) indicates to me that you may not even be roleplaying, and thus we're talking apples and oranges.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;Many of the NPCs are created for the sole purpose of dieing to the PCs. The GM spawns these NPCs as needed.&quot;<br>
<br>
So what?  They're stilled HUMAN CONTROLLED.  That's the key distinction you're missing.  <br>
<br>
You're just making my point for me.  Every P&amp;P RPG is based on conflict between HUMAN CONTROLLED CHARACTERS.<br>
<br>
As for their sole purpose being &quot;dying to the PCs,&quot; I repeat my comments above. <br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&quot;Most PnP games do not have much, or encourage any PvP. &quot;<br>
<br>
You miss the point again.  I am not talking about MMORPGs &quot;encouraging&quot; PvP or having &quot;much&quot; PvP  (now using your definition of PvP as conflict between the characters controlled by non-GMs).  Where did you get the idea?<br>
<br>
Even apart from the core conflict between human controlled characters (controlled by the GM and the &quot;players&quot;), ALL P&amp;P RPGs have the possibility and potential of conflict between characters controlled by the &quot;players&quot; (meaning non-GMs) .  Every single one of them.  <br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/7/01 9:12:35 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/rtfm.gif width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> Tsukune says:  <b><i>PvP is player vs player conflict. Players are not GMs. GMs have the power to change the world in a sentance. Players don't.</b></i><br>
<br>
The distinction is not between PvP, PvGM, PvV or what not.<br>
<br>
It's between "human intelligence" and "artificial intelligence".  Scirocco's thesis is that old-style AD&D always pitted the participants against human intelligence, much in the same way PvP in modern MMRPGs pits players against human intelligence.  I see no flaws in that thesis.<br>
<br>
Human intelligence is always preferable over artificial intelligence.  Artificial intelligence is just a crutch when the game designer can't supply enough human intelligence to satisfy the gamers (mainly due to their relative numbers).  If the game designer wants a game targeted to the serious, long-term player interested in a deep and involved world, he or she should strive to make the ratio of AI to HI as low as possible.  EQ, unfortunately, has done precisely the opposite. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uaaroan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aaroan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/7/01 9:21:02 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/foolthatspeaks/bartxxx.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EVERY P&amp;P RPG is based on PvP</span><hr size=1> - accountiblity can be accomplished by having kos lists where that kos(kos to that guild or to you) appears with in line of sight.<br>
