<br>
 &quot;It's between &quot;human intelligence&quot; and &quot;artificial intelligence&quot;. Scirocco's thesis is that old-style AD&amp;D always pitted the participants against human intelligence, much in the same way PvP in modern MMRPGs pits players against human intelligence. I see no flaws in that thesis.&quot;<br>
<br>
 If this is Scirocco's thesis, then I have to disagree with it.  I _don't_ think that old-style AD&amp;D is much the same as PvP in modern MMRPGs.  If someone wants to change the words and say something like HCCvHCC, hey, that's fine.  And I'm happy to call AD&amp;D that.  But HCCvHCC != PvP, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
 I guess, from my point of view, I think of GMs (or Verant) as &quot;referees&quot;.  The referee in a football game is _not_ a player, for example.  We used to say, as players, that we're &quot;playing in a campaign&quot; or &quot;running [a character] in a campaign&quot;.  As a GM, I never said this.  I'd say that I was &quot;running a campaign&quot; (note the lack of &quot;in&quot;).<br>
<br>
 This is an interesting discussion, but it hinges upon agreeing to a definition some of us are unwilling to accept, methinks. ;)<br>
